title: Jacqueline  Magyar CRIME REPORT/ INCIDENT FOR 2024/ 2025 (Redondo Beach City Clerk)

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I'm requesting any crime /incident/ supplement / allegations reports that were made against my home,  myself, and any vehicles parked at my house , that been pulled over or impounded.. starting from 8/26/2024 to present. I would also like to request the incident report my husband Michael Vizzini had made I believe somewhere the beginning of October 2024 regarding his vehicle that was stolen 2015 Chevy Silvarado, including his safes that were stolen, and the phone calls he made for his Restraining order  that was violated. I would to request a receipt for the search at my home that I never received  for the items that were taken from my home. And also a complete copy of the search warrant, which I was only given the 1st and last page after they were done searching my home.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

jacqueline Magyar Vizzini

title: RFK Meeting and Communications with Ed Martin

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: RFK Meeting and Communications with Ed Martin
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Any audio recordings, video recordings, or transcripts of the March 18, 2025, meeting involving Secretary Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., and Acting U.S. Attorney Ed Martin.

2. Any notes taken during the March 18, 2025, meeting involving Secretary Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., and Acting U.S. Attorney Ed Martin.

3. Any memoranda, summaries, or minutes concerning the March 18, 2025, meeting involving Secretary Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., and Acting U.S. Attorney Ed Martin.

4. All documents, communications, emails, calendar invitations, scheduling notes, agendas, briefing materials, or background documents prepared in advance of, or related to, planning and arranging the March 18 meeting involving Secretary Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., and Acting U.S. Attorney Ed Martin.

5. All written communications, including emails, letters, or messages, between the Office of the Secretary of Health and Human Services (HHS) and the Office of the U.S. Attorney for the District of Columbia on or after January 20, 2025.

6. Any communications, emails, memoranda, or other documents within HHS that reference or discuss the March 18, 2025, meeting involving Secretary Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., and Acting U.S. Attorney Ed Martin.

7. Any written materials exchanged during (or referenced in any agenda for) the March 18, 2025, meeting involving Secretary Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., and Acting U.S. Attorney Ed Martin.

8. Any communications to or from Andrew Nixon referencing "Ed Martin" or the Office of the U.S. Attorney for the District of Columbia.

"Communications" means and includes emails, text messages, social media messages, letters, memoranda, calendar entries, chats, or any form of one-to-one or one-to-many communication.

Please note that this request seeks public records wherever they may be found, including on devices or networks owned or operated by private parties. For example, if an employee uses a personal cell phone or social media account to conduct public business, records created, maintained, or held on the phone or account are public records subject to this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

title: Request to FBI for all communications with author Thomas Harris

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request to FBI for all communications with author Thomas Harris
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All communications between the FBI and Thomas Harris (born William Thomas Harris III, on September 22, 1940, in Jackson, Tennessee), author of "Silence of the Lambs," within the records retention schedule(s) of the relevant office(s). Such communications may include, but should not be limited to, emails, correspondence, memos, and transcriptions of telephone calls. 

A previous request from me was rejected by the FBI on the grounds that it would violate Mr. Harris's personal privacy to even acknowledge the existence of such records. As I wrote in my appeal, which was never processed, I do not think this provision applies to my request. To show this, I will first limit the scope of my request to communications between Mr. Harris and the FBI to those communications which are relevant to Mr. Harris's professional work as a writer and novelist. Such communications could not involve a reasonable expectation that they would not be subject to FOIA. Furthermore, even if certain third-party communications are not subject to FOIA, the FBI's own written communications are still subject to FOIA, and my request includes communications from the FBI.

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. title: Alleged Unlawful Sensitive/Classified Technology Transfer at CalTech/JPL (Federal Bureau of Investigation)

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records pertaining to alleged espionage and/or violation(s) of the Arms Export Control Act and/or International Traffic in Arms Regulations at the California Institute of Technology and/or the Jet Propulsion Laboratory between 2010 and 2017, inclusive. The records I am requesting include, but are not limited to, alleged criminal conduct pertaining to the Electrospray Thruster Array Technology Feasibility Study, which was funded, in part, by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency.

In addition to a search of your agency's general and/or central indices I request that your agency also search: 1) Any "cross-referenced" records relevant to this inquiry; and, 2) "ELSUR" (Electronic Surveillance) records; and, 3) the Sentinel database; and, 4) the Investigative Data Warehouse; and, 5) the Data Integration and Visualization System.

This request is for any and all responsive records at all relevant FBI offices and facilities including, but not limited to, HQ and relevant field offices in Los Angeles County, California.

In order to facilitate the location of the requested records I am providing the following list of names that may be associated with these allegations and any related FBI investigation: Amir Gat, Sandra Troian, Daniel Weihs, Morteza Gharib, Kelly M. Sullivan, and, David Tsang.

Upon information and belief, Kelly M. Sullivan and David Tsang were FBI agents with the Los Angeles County Counterintelligence Division at the times relevant to this request. The personal names provided above should not be construed as a basis for limiting the scope of this records request.

In order to help to determine my status to assess fees, you should know that I am a representative of the news media affiliated with the Randolph Bourne Institute and its media outlet, Antiwar.com. This request is made as part of news gathering and not for a commercial use.

I request a waiver of all fees for this request. Disclosure of the requested information is in the public interest because it is likely to contribute significantly to public understanding of the operations or activities of the government and is not primarily in my commercial interest. Specifically, this information will help advance public understanding of foreign intelligence activities targeted against the United States of America.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Michelle Kinnucan

title: Request to DoD for 2023 budget of Community Engagement Office

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request to DoD for 2023 budget of Community Engagement Office
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The annual budget report for the Department of Defense's Community Engagement Office, for the year 2023.

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation as well as the editor-in-chief and a contributor to a research magazine published by said foundation titled "Cultural Engineering Studies." These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

title: New York FOIL Policies (Department of Health and Mental Hygiene)

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

1. Annual reports prepared by or for the agency that detail response times, compliance statistics, or other data related to the processing of public records requests. If quarterly or monthly reports are available, please also provide those. 

2. Statistical data or reports regarding the agency’s (a) average, (b) median, (c) shortest, and (d) longest processing times for public records requests for each year from January 1, 2020 to present.

3. Records showing the total number of public records requests pending as of the date of this request. If available, please include a breakdown of pending requests by duration (e.g., pending less than 30 days, 30–90 days, more than 90 days).

4. Policies, procedures, guidelines, memoranda, or training materials concerning how the agency determines or calculates the "statement of the approximate date, which shall be reasonable under the circumstances, when the request will be granted or denied," as required by Public Officers Law § 89(3)(a).

Requests 1, 2, and 4 are limited to records generated or in use on or after January 1, 2020.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh
